node.text:
A soulful reminder from @jayshettygenius 👆 Comment a YES below if you needed this today.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
@jayshettygenius is a way for you to access weekly workshops and meditations that nourish your WHOLE self— mentally, emotionally, and spiritually. You're reminded that to unlock your highest potential, you must first intentionally and consistently care for your soul. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
And at the end of the day, that's what Genius is all about.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
🌟 intentional⁠⁠
💫 consistent⁠⁠
❤️ care⁠⁠
🙏 for your soul⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Join us in this Sunday's workshop and meditation. I can't wait to see you there.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Link in bio to join now 🔗 jayshettygenius.com

node.text: Leave a “YES” below if you value presence in a conversation👇 Set rules and boundaries around communication. If someone is working or on their phone ask them for their attention. Not demand but just ask. Express that you have something important to share. And when someone asks, make sure you listen. With attention. with affection. With kindness. You never know how much they need it.

node.text: @proctorgallagher👇 (link in bio) This week I got to talk to Bob about freeing yourself from societal and cultural control, seeking awareness and learning how to improve your life, and finding the dedication to pursue what you love.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by Jay Shetty on July 18, 2021 tagging @jayshetty. May be an image of 2 people and people sitting.

node.text:
This was my best friend during my time as a monk. His name was Janakinath Das (JD). 9 years ago, we had just completed a presentation to some university students on how trying to serve the world with our gifts is the most worthy pursuit of human life. You can see the abundant and infectious smile he has on his face here, I’ve actually never seen him without it and neither has anyone I know. 

3 days ago I got a message from one of the senior monks who was with him. It was 11.40pm there but I called him on FaceTime immediately. He was emaciated, hunched over and mostly bones. He’d been fighting cancer for 4 years. Not only personally, but through raising awareness, raising money and helping other patients through meditation retreats and seminars. He even gave a TEDx talk on his experience all the while battling with the disease himself. 

Still 3 days ago, he was beaming. All I could see was his smile. Emaciated but ecstatic, hunched over but hungry to serve, in pain but full of joyful presence. We laughed, shared memories and he shared lessons with me. He was only 2 years older than me, but in this moment I recognized he was far more realized and prepared for death. He was grateful for the time he had with everyone, he was appreciative of the monks that had been helping him in his time of need and he was joyful with the experience he had gone through. Even in this critical state, he was not complaining, criticizing or comparing. He was conscious, compassionate and complete. He specifically told me to never wish for what you don’t want, the pain you don’t want to feel or the ordeals you don’t want to go through as they are most likely the medicine that will be used for our detachment. 

Read on in comments…

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Jay Shetty on July 18, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'You cannot change their behavior by loving them harder Emma Grace'.

node.text: Drop a ❤️ if you felt this👇Loving someone harder can give them encouragement but not change them. Give someone love because you want to give them strength and support, not to change them because that expectation will always be unmet. We love someone because we care for them. Not to change them. We love someone because of our own compassion and empathy.

node.text: @willowsmith I’m so grateful to know you and in awe of the journey you’ve been on! I deeply admire your dedication to your study, personal practices and how you express it through your art! You are an old soul and have so much to offer the world and I’m so excited to see what you share through this experience! We love you!

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Jay Shetty on July 17, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Real friends don't dampen your light. They help you find the light in the darkness Jay Shetty'.

node.text: Tag 4 real ones below👇We all want real friends but don’t forget to be one as well. When your friend shares good news, before you judge, criticize or dampen the mood take a moment to listen and be happy for them. Celebrate their successes and wins. We all want to see our friends grow but we have to assist at the right time.
